DDI-DrugBank.d237.s13|7-141| Coadministration of grapefruit juice with cisapride increases the bioavailability of cisapride and concomitant use should be avoided. |drug
DDI-DrugBank.d237.s13|143-258| It is important to note that the safety and efficacy of this drug have not been established in pediatric patients. |drug
DDI-DrugBank.d237.s13|260-371| The drug should be used with caution in patients over 65 years of age and in patients with hepatic impairment. |drug
DDI-DrugBank.d237.s13|373-434| The drug may cause diarrhea, nausea, vomiting, and headache. |drug
DDI-DrugBank.d237.s13|436-632| The drug may cause QT prolongation and should be used with caution in patients with a history of QT prolongation, risk of hypokalemia, and those taking other drugs that may cause QT prolongation. |drug
DDI-DrugBank.d237.s13|634-751| The drug may cause increased heart rate, and may cause tachycardia, ventricular tachycardia, and torsade de pointes. |drug
DDI-DrugBank.d237.s13|753-935| The drug may cause hyperglycemia, and should be used with caution in patients with diabetes mellitus, patients with a history of diabetes, and patients with impaired renal function. |drug
